AB  - The thesis addresses the possible channels of monetary policy influence on the
decline of output in Russia. In particular, it considers the role of interenterprise arrears in
the transmission process, as well as the question of whether monetary impulses could affect
the sectoral pattern of the industrial recession. It appeal's that the fall in output related to
monetary contraction may be significant, given the deficiencies of the credit market, while
distortions associated with the policy (which resulted in a lack of liquid assets in the system
and was translated into the outburst of quasi-money and extremely high interest rates) may
lengthen the recession.
Underdevelopment of the financial sector alters the propagation mechanisms of
monetary impulses. The lending channel, which is likely to remain the main channel in
initial stages of transition, is significantly modified in comparison with the one in
developed economies. On the supply side the lack of adequate substitutes for the Central
bank of Russia (CBR) loanable funds, reflecting the structural weakness of the banking
system, intensifies the decline of credit supply in periods of monetary tightening. On the
demand side the lack of substitutes for bank credit deepens enterprise-side reaction,
adversely affecting the viability of firms in the long-run.
We examine the role of interenterprise arrears using a two-sector (energy vs
manufacturing) non-Walrasian general equilibrium model with price regulation and credit
rationing. The model explains the transactions’ role of money and reveals that
interenterprise arrears may soften or strengthen production-side responses to monetary
impulse in the steady state (if compared with the case when no arrears are allowed). The
precise results depend on the characteristics of the production function and the transaction
cost function, and the level of real money balances. Empirical evidence appears to favor the
“cushioning” effect of arrears.
The model allows one to highlight the mechanisms through which policy, meant to
fight inflation, could cause an increase in inflation together with a decline of both sectors’
output and consumption. Two versions of the model are considered: one with credit
rationing of both sectors, and one with asymmetric rationing. The latter appeal's to receive
significant empirical support for 1994-96, suggesting that deeper decline in the
manufacturing sector may partially, along with other reasons, be explained by its higher
exposure to credit-rationing, and therefore, higher losses associated with monetary
tightening. A relaxation of the credit rationing constraint to the second sector, and/or a
decrease in interest rates, may be growth promoting strategies, implying that there is scope
for governmental intervention
