Degree: Ph.D.DegreeYear: 1981Institute: Brown UniversityA primary characteristic of the equilibrium business cycle model exposited by Lucas, Barro and others is that only the unperceived and unanticipated part of monetary growth causes output fluctuations. This characteristic is an implication of the four theoretical underpinnings of the model, (1) rational expectations, (2) a market-clearing structure that incorporates the natural rate hypothesis, (3) incomplete information about real and monetary disturbances, (4) a nondeterministic specification of these key exogenous variables. The dichotomy of the effects of monetary growth between unperceived-nonneutral and perceived-neutral growth implies that any feedback monetary policy will have no effect on current output. However this dichotomy also implies, in a world of contemporaneously perceived money growth, that any observed money stock changes cannot cause changes in current output. The model in this essay formally develops the theoretical relation between price and quantity determination and contemporaneously perceived money growth in the equilibrium model. The theoretical structure is extended to account for monetary feedback policy, persistence effects, the apparent gradualness of error discovery in preliminary monetary data and correlation between errors in monetary data. The primary prediction of the theoretical model is that innovations to aggregate output have zero covariance with current and past values of preliminary monetary growth. This implication of the equilibrium model is a testable hypothesis. This hypothesis was tested using post-Korean War U.S. data on industrial production, the employment rate as real variables and a newly constructed quarterly series on contemporaneously observed monetary growth (M1). The actual tests took the form of a regression of current output on past output and past values of contemporaneously observed money growth. The hypothesis that supports the model is that the monetary variables contribute no explanatory power in this regression equation. The preponderance of evidence from the statistical tests indicates that contemporaneously observed money growth did influence output over the sample period.A second testable hypothesis drawn from the theory relates to the unperceived-nonneutral part of monetary growth. Specifically the theory predicts that the revisions to contemporaneously observed money represent a potentially important source of unperceived money growth and should have nonneutral output effects. Because of intertemporal correlations between exogenous variables and the gradualness of error discovery in preliminary monetary data, the testable hypothesis that supports the equilibrium model is that in a regression of current output on lagged output and current and lagged revisions the monetary revisions should have a positive and significant effect on current output. The revised M1 series used to construct this test was the historical M1 series known as of January 1980. The preponderance of evidence from extensive tests of the second hypothesis is that monetary revisions do not have the predicted effect on output.The conclusion of this study, based on the above empirical findings, is that the equilibrium model cannot explain the data. The negative conclusion is disturbing in the sense that the equilibrium model, until now, provided a theoretical setup that was consistent with the idea that agents exploit perceived gains from trade and could explain the apparent causal relation of money in the business cycle. The rejection of this model leaves modern business cycle theory without an explanation for economic fluctuations that is theoretically appealing and has strong empirical support.

